## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across a pattern that shows up in breach reports over and over again — organizations that were aware of a vulnerability but deprioritized it because they assumed they were not a likely target. The **2020 Universal Health Services ransomware attack** is a good example of this. One of the largest hospital networks in the US, brought down by ransomware, with staff reverting to pen and paper during the recovery. The cost was estimated at around $67 million.

What I took from that: *"we are too small to be targeted"* is not a risk management strategy. And even large, well-resourced organizations get caught off guard when they underestimate likelihood. The question that stuck with me is not *"will someone target us?"* but *"if they did, how prepared would we be?"*

That question feels like the right starting point for everything risk management is trying to do.

